variable.variable_description: Plasminogen is the proenzyme of plasmin, the major enzyme that degrades fibrin clots. Measured using ELISA.
PAI-1 is the primary inhibitor of both tissue-type plasminogen activator (tPA) and urinary-type plasminogen activator (uPA) [2]. Measured using ELISA.

Thrombomodulin (TM) is an endothelial cell surface receptor specific for thrombin. TM is involved in promoting activation of the anticoagulant protein C pathway during coagulation [3]. Soluble TM is the product of proteolytic degradation of endothelial-bound TM. When the endothelium is damaged, endothelial-bound TM is released from the endothelial surface, resulting in a significant increase in sTM concentration [4]. Measured using ELISA.
Clot lysis time is measured by a functional assay in which a thrombin induced fibrin clot is lysed by exogenously added tissue plasminogen activator [5]
Fibrinogen is the main structural protein in the blood responsible for forming clots, it is converted into fibrin by thrombin. Measured using ELISA.
Proenzyme of TAFIa. Measured using ELISA.
alpha2-antiplasmin is the major circulating inhibitor of plasmin. Measured using ELISA.
TAT is a complex composed of thrombin and its inhibitor, antithrombin, in equal proportions [6]. Measured using ELISA.
Fibrinolysis inhibitor activated by thrombin, plasmin, or the thrombin-thrombomodulin complex. TAFIa functional assay measures how much TAFIa activity is present in plasma.
